{"id":"1709.03385","submitter":"Mike Winkler","authors":"Mike Winkler","title":"The algorithmic structure of the finite stopping time behavior of the 3x\n  + 1 function","comments":"24 pages, 5 figures, 4 tables, 7 programs/algorithms in PARI/GP,\n  Edits: shortened abstract, corrected typos on p.7, addition of A293308 on p.1\n  and p.9, corrected font for \"mod\"","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The $3x + 1$ problem concerns iteration of the map\n$T:\\mathbb{Z}\\rightarrow\\mathbb{Z}$ given by \\begin{align*}\nT(x)=\\left\\{\\begin{array}{lcr}\\;\\;\\;\\;\\displaystyle{\\frac{x}{2}} & \\mbox{if\n$\\,x\\equiv 0\\ (mod\\ 2)$}, \\displaystyle{\\frac{3x+1}{2}} & \\mbox{if $\\,x\\equiv\n1\\ (mod\\ 2)$}.\\end{array}\\right. \\end{align*} The $3x+1$ Conjecture states that\nevery $x\\geq1$ has some iterate $T^s(x)=1$. The least $s\\in\\mathbb{N}$ such\nthat $T^s(x)<x$ is called the stopping time of $x$. It is shown that the\nresidue classes of the integers $x>1$ with a finite stopping time can be\nevolved according to a directed rooted tree based on their parity vectors. Each\nparity vector represents a unique Diophantine equation whose only positive\nsolutions are the integers with a finite stopping time. The tree structure is\nbased on a precise algorithm which allows accurate statements about the\nsolutions $x$ without solving the Diophantine equations explicitly. As a\nconsequence, the integers $x>1$ with a finite stopping time can be generated\nalgorithmically. It is also shown that the OEIS sequences A076227 and A100982\nrelated to the residues $(mod\\ 2^k)$ can be generated algorithmically in a\nPascal's triangle-like manner from the two starting values 0 and 1. Summarized,\nthe results of this paper present a fully self-contained theory of the $3x+1$\nstopping time problem. For the results no statistical and probability\ntheoretical methods were used.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 6 Sep 2017 01:00:05 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 21 Sep 2017 14:08:45 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sun, 26 Nov 2017 12:36:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-11-28"}
